/* ============================================================================
   linux+ :: content/domain4.js
   Lazy-loaded textbook reading module for XK0-006 Domain 4 (Automation, Orchestration, and Scripting).
   Populates LINUXPLUS.reading[4]. Loaded on demand by app.js.
   ============================================================================ */
window.LINUXPLUS = window.LINUXPLUS || {}; LINUXPLUS.reading = LINUXPLUS.reading || {};
LINUXPLUS.reading[4] = [];
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Automation and Orchestration Concepts", body:"<p>Modern Linux administration rarely means logging into a single box and typing commands by hand. Fleets of dozens, hundreds, or thousands of systems demand <span class='keyterm'>automation</span> -- the practice of letting software perform repetitive configuration and operational tasks without human intervention. The Linux+ exam expects you to distinguish automation from orchestration and to understand the design principles that make automation reliable, repeatable, and safe at scale.</p><h3>Automation versus Orchestration</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Automation</span> is the execution of a single task or a small bounded set of tasks without manual effort: installing a package, editing a config file, restarting a service. <span class='keyterm'>Orchestration</span> is the coordination of many automated tasks across many systems into a larger workflow, with attention to order, dependencies, and state. Deploying a web application -- provisioning servers, configuring a database, rolling out app code, then registering everything with a load balancer in the right sequence -- is orchestration. Put simply, automation handles one step; orchestration choreographs the whole dance. The two are complementary: orchestrators invoke automation primitives as their building blocks. A useful mental model is that automation removes the manual effort from a step, while orchestration removes the manual effort from deciding the <em>order</em> and <em>dependencies</em> of many steps. A scheduled cron job that rotates logs is automation; a tool that drains a node, patches it, reboots it, verifies health, and only then moves to the next node is orchestration.</p><h3>Infrastructure as Code</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Infrastructure as Code (IaC)</span> is the practice of defining servers, networks, and configuration in machine-readable text files rather than by clicking through consoles or running ad-hoc commands. Because the definitions are files, they live in version control, can be peer-reviewed, diffed, rolled back, and reproduced identically across environments. The same code that builds the staging environment builds production, eliminating the drift and snowflake servers that plague hand-built infrastructure. IaC also doubles as living documentation: the repository <em>is</em> the authoritative description of what the environment should look like.</p><h3>Declarative versus Imperative</h3><p>IaC tools fall into two paradigms. An <span class='keyterm'>imperative</span> approach specifies the exact steps to reach a goal -- run this, then that. A <span class='keyterm'>declarative</span> approach describes the desired end state and lets the tool figure out how to get there. Declaring <em>the package nginx is present and the service is running</em> leaves it to the tool to decide whether to install, do nothing, or start the service. Most configuration management favors declarative definitions because they are easier to reason about and naturally idempotent. A plain shell script that runs <code>dnf install -y nginx</code> is imperative; an Ansible task with <code>state: present</code> is declarative.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Automation</td><td>One task done without human effort</td><td>Restart a service</td></tr><tr><td>Orchestration</td><td>Many tasks coordinated into a workflow</td><td>Roll out a full app stack</td></tr><tr><td>Declarative</td><td>Describe the desired end state</td><td><code>state: present</code></td></tr><tr><td>Imperative</td><td>Describe the exact steps to run</td><td><code>dnf install -y nginx</code></td></tr><tr><td>Idempotent</td><td>Re-running yields the same result</td><td>Second run reports <em>ok</em></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Idempotency</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Idempotency</span> means an operation produces the same result no matter how many times it runs. A well-written automation task can be applied repeatedly without changing the system after the first successful run: if the package is already installed, the tool reports <em>ok</em> rather than reinstalling. Idempotency is what makes it safe to re-run a playbook against a fleet to enforce a known-good state. Contrast a non-idempotent shell line <code>echo 'PermitRootLogin no' &gt;&gt; /etc/ssh/sshd_config</code>, which appends the line on <em>every</em> run and eventually fills the file with duplicates, against a declarative module that ensures the line is present exactly once.</p><h3>Agent versus Agentless</h3><p>Configuration management tools differ in how they reach managed nodes. An <span class='keyterm'>agent-based</span> tool installs a persistent daemon on every node that periodically pulls policy from a central server -- Puppet and Chef work this way. An <span class='keyterm'>agentless</span> tool needs nothing pre-installed; it pushes configuration over an existing protocol such as SSH -- this is Ansible's model. Agentless tooling lowers the barrier to entry because there is nothing to bootstrap on new hosts, while agent-based tooling scales well and continuously enforces state. The push model (agentless) is admin-initiated; the pull model (agent) is node-initiated on a schedule. Each model has operational consequences worth understanding. Push tooling gives the operator immediate, on-demand control -- you run a command and changes apply now -- but it does not enforce state between runs, so drift can creep in until the next push. Pull tooling enforces state continuously because every node checks in on its own timer, but it requires bootstrapping an agent and a central server, and changes take effect only at the next check-in interval rather than instantly. Many large environments blend both: a pull-based agent for continuous baseline enforcement and a push-based tool for urgent, coordinated rollouts.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>How it reaches nodes</th><th>Tools</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Agent-based (pull)</td><td>Daemon on node pulls policy on a timer</td><td>Puppet, Chef</td></tr><tr><td>Agentless (push)</td><td>Admin pushes over SSH/WinRM, no daemon</td><td>Ansible, Salt (SSH mode)</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Remember the one-line distinctions: automation is a single task, orchestration coordinates many. Declarative says <em>what</em>, imperative says <em>how</em>. Idempotent means safe to re-run. Ansible is agentless over SSH (push); Puppet and Chef are agent-based (pull).</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A junior admin adds <code>useradd deploy</code> to a provisioning script. The second run fails with <em>user already exists</em> and aborts the whole script. Rewriting it declaratively -- an Ansible <code>user</code> task with <code>state: present</code> -- makes it idempotent, so reruns simply report <em>ok</em> and the script continues.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Infrastructure as Code with Ansible", body:"<p><span class='keyterm'>Ansible</span> is the most heavily tested configuration management tool on Linux+, prized for being agentless and easy to read. It connects to managed nodes over <span class='keyterm'>SSH</span> (and WinRM for Windows), copies small programs called modules to the target, runs them, and removes them -- so no daemon ever has to live on the node. The control node needs only Python and the <code>ansible</code> package; managed nodes need only SSH access and a Python interpreter. Because everything rides over SSH, Ansible inherits SSH's authentication (keys, agents) and needs no new ports opened.</p><h3>The Inventory</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>inventory</span> lists the hosts Ansible manages, grouped logically. A simple INI-style inventory looks like: <code>[web]</code> on one line, then <code>web1.example.com</code> and <code>web2.example.com</code>, then <code>[db]</code> and the database hosts. The default file is <code>/etc/ansible/hosts</code>, but most projects keep a local <code>inventory</code> file referenced with <code>-i</code>. Inventories can also be written in YAML and can be <em>dynamic</em>, generated by a script that queries a cloud provider for the current list of instances. Group variables live in <code>group_vars/web.yml</code> and host-specific values in <code>host_vars/web1.yml</code>, keeping data out of the playbook.</p><h3>Ad-hoc Commands</h3><p>For one-off actions you run an <span class='keyterm'>ad-hoc command</span> with the <code>ansible</code> binary and a module specified by <code>-m</code>. To ping every host: <code>ansible all -m ping</code>. To install a package: <code>ansible web -m dnf -a 'name=httpd state=present' --become</code>. The <code>-a</code> flag passes arguments and <code>--become</code> escalates to root. Ad-hoc commands are perfect for quick checks but are not reusable, version-controlled, or self-documenting the way a playbook is.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Inventory</td><td>List of managed hosts, grouped</td></tr><tr><td>Playbook</td><td>YAML file of plays and tasks</td></tr><tr><td>Play</td><td>Maps a host group to tasks</td></tr><tr><td>Task</td><td>A single call to a module</td></tr><tr><td>Module</td><td>Reusable unit of work (dnf, copy, service)</td></tr><tr><td>Role</td><td>Packaged, reusable set of tasks and files</td></tr><tr><td>Handler</td><td>Task triggered by notify only on change</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Playbooks and YAML</h3><p>The heart of Ansible is the <span class='keyterm'>playbook</span>, a <span class='keyterm'>YAML</span> file describing a set of <span class='keyterm'>plays</span>, each mapping a group of hosts to an ordered list of <span class='keyterm'>tasks</span>. Each task calls a <span class='keyterm'>module</span> -- a reusable unit such as <code>dnf</code>, <code>copy</code>, <code>template</code>, <code>service</code>, or <code>user</code>. A minimal playbook, written with YAML indentation, reads like this:</p><pre><code>---\n- name: Configure web servers\n  hosts: web\n  become: true\n  tasks:\n    - name: Install nginx\n      dnf:\n        name: nginx\n        state: present\n    - name: Start and enable nginx\n      service:\n        name: nginx\n        state: started\n        enabled: true</code></pre><p>You run it with <code>ansible-playbook -i inventory site.yml</code>. Because the modules are declarative and idempotent, re-running reports <em>ok</em> for anything already in the desired state and <em>changed</em> only for what it had to alter. A typical run ends with a recap line such as <code>web1 : ok=3 changed=1 unreachable=0 failed=0</code>. Use <code>--check</code> for a dry run that predicts changes without applying them, and <code>-v</code> through <code>-vvvv</code> for increasing verbosity when debugging.</p><h3>Roles and Galaxy</h3><p>As playbooks grow, you organize reusable pieces into <span class='keyterm'>roles</span>. A role is a directory with a fixed layout -- <code>tasks/</code>, <code>handlers/</code>, <code>templates/</code>, <code>files/</code>, <code>vars/</code>, and <code>defaults/</code> -- that bundles everything needed to configure one concern, such as a web server. Playbooks include roles by name, and the community shares thousands of pre-built roles through <span class='keyterm'>Ansible Galaxy</span> (<code>ansible-galaxy install geerlingguy.nginx</code>). A <span class='keyterm'>handler</span> is a special task triggered by <code>notify</code> only when something changes, commonly used to restart a service after its config file is updated -- so the service bounces once, at the end of the play, only if its config actually changed.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>ansible all -m ping</code></td><td>Ad-hoc connectivity check</td></tr><tr><td><code>ansible-playbook site.yml</code></td><td>Run a playbook</td></tr><tr><td><code>ansible-playbook --check</code></td><td>Dry run (predict changes)</td></tr><tr><td><code>ansible-galaxy install</code></td><td>Download a community role</td></tr><tr><td><code>ansible-vault encrypt</code></td><td>Encrypt secrets in a file</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Know that Ansible is agentless and uses SSH and YAML. The command to run a playbook is <code>ansible-playbook</code>; the command for a one-off task is <code>ansible</code> with <code>-m module -a args</code>. Privilege escalation is <code>--become</code> on the CLI or <code>become: true</code> in a play. A dry run is <code>--check</code>.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>You update an nginx config template, but the service does not pick up changes. The fix is a <code>handler</code> named 'restart nginx' that the template task triggers with <code>notify: restart nginx</code> -- the service restarts automatically, but only on the runs where the template actually changed.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Puppet and OpenTofu", body:"<p>Beyond Ansible, Linux+ expects familiarity with two other IaC tools that take different approaches: <span class='keyterm'>Puppet</span>, an agent-based configuration manager, and <span class='keyterm'>OpenTofu</span> (the open-source fork of Terraform), a declarative infrastructure provisioner. Knowing which tool fits which job -- configuring existing servers versus building the servers themselves -- is a recurring exam theme.</p><h3>Puppet Architecture</h3><p>Puppet typically runs in a <span class='keyterm'>master/agent</span> model. Every managed node runs a <span class='keyterm'>Puppet agent</span> daemon that periodically -- usually every 30 minutes -- contacts the <span class='keyterm'>Puppet master</span> (server), sends facts about itself gathered by a tool called <em>facter</em>, and receives a compiled <span class='keyterm'>catalog</span> describing its desired state. The agent then enforces that catalog locally and reports back. Because enforcement repeats on a schedule, Puppet continuously corrects drift -- if someone edits a managed file by hand, the next run reverts it. A standalone mode, <code>puppet apply manifest.pp</code>, runs a manifest locally without a master.</p><h3>Manifests, Modules, and Certificates</h3><p>Puppet policy is written in its own declarative language in files called <span class='keyterm'>manifests</span> with a <code>.pp</code> extension. A manifest declares <em>resources</em> -- a package, a file, a service -- and their desired attributes. A small manifest looks like this:</p><pre><code>package { 'nginx':\n  ensure =&gt; installed,\n}\nservice { 'nginx':\n  ensure  =&gt; running,\n  enable  =&gt; true,\n  require =&gt; Package['nginx'],\n}</code></pre><p>Related manifests, templates, and files are packaged into <span class='keyterm'>modules</span>, Puppet's unit of reuse, shared through the Puppet Forge. Trust between agent and master is established with <span class='keyterm'>certificates</span>: on first contact the agent generates a certificate signing request, and the administrator signs it on the master with <code>puppetserver ca sign --certname newnode</code>. Until the cert is signed, the agent cannot receive a catalog -- a common gotcha when onboarding a new node.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Puppet term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Agent</td><td>Daemon on each node that pulls policy</td></tr><tr><td>Master / server</td><td>Compiles and serves catalogs</td></tr><tr><td>Manifest (.pp)</td><td>File declaring desired resources</td></tr><tr><td>Module</td><td>Packaged, reusable manifests + files</td></tr><tr><td>Catalog</td><td>Compiled desired-state document for a node</td></tr><tr><td>Facter / facts</td><td>Tool that gathers node facts</td></tr><tr><td>Certificate</td><td>Signed trust between agent and master</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>OpenTofu and Terraform</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>OpenTofu</span> is a community-driven fork of HashiCorp's Terraform, sharing the same configuration language and workflow. Where Ansible and Puppet excel at configuring existing servers, OpenTofu excels at <em>provisioning</em> the infrastructure itself -- cloud instances, networks, DNS records, load balancers. Configuration is written in <span class='keyterm'>HCL</span> (HashiCorp Configuration Language) in <code>.tf</code> files that declare <span class='keyterm'>resources</span>, such as a virtual machine or a storage bucket, in a fully declarative style. A resource block reads <code>resource 'aws_instance' 'web' { ami = 'ami-123'; instance_type = 't3.micro' }</code>.</p><h3>State, Plan, and Apply</h3><p>OpenTofu tracks what it has built in a <span class='keyterm'>state file</span> (<code>terraform.tfstate</code>), a JSON record mapping declared resources to real-world objects. The workflow is three commands: <code>tofu init</code> downloads provider plugins; <code>tofu plan</code> compares your <code>.tf</code> files against the state and shows exactly what it will create, change, or destroy without doing anything; and <code>tofu apply</code> executes that plan. The plan step is a critical safety feature -- you review the diff (lines marked <code>+</code> create, <code>-</code> destroy, <code>~</code> change) before any real resources change. Because the state file is the source of truth, it is usually stored in shared <span class='keyterm'>remote state</span> (an object store) with locking, so a whole team does not corrupt it with simultaneous applies.</p><h3>Choosing the Right Tool</h3><p>The three tools are not competitors so much as complements, and the exam likes to test which one fits a given job. Reach for <span class='keyterm'>OpenTofu/Terraform</span> when you need to <em>create</em> the underlying infrastructure -- spin up virtual machines, define networks, allocate storage, register DNS. Reach for <span class='keyterm'>Puppet</span> or <span class='keyterm'>Ansible</span> when the servers already exist and you need to <em>configure</em> what runs inside them -- install packages, write config files, manage services and users. A common real-world pipeline uses OpenTofu to provision a fresh fleet of cloud instances, then hands the new IP addresses to Ansible to configure the operating system and applications on each one. Puppet's strength is its relentless, scheduled drift correction; Ansible's is its agentless simplicity and readable YAML; OpenTofu's is its plan-before-apply provisioning of cloud resources tracked in state.</p><table><thead><tr><th>OpenTofu command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>tofu init</code></td><td>Download providers, init backend</td></tr><tr><td><code>tofu plan</code></td><td>Preview create/change/destroy</td></tr><tr><td><code>tofu apply</code></td><td>Execute the planned changes</td></tr><tr><td><code>tofu destroy</code></td><td>Tear down managed resources</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Puppet is agent-based: manifests (<code>.pp</code>), modules, catalogs, and certificate signing. OpenTofu/Terraform provisions infrastructure declaratively in HCL (<code>.tf</code>), tracks reality in a <code>.tfstate</code> file, and follows init -&gt; plan -&gt; apply. Always review <code>plan</code> output before <code>apply</code>.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A new server's Puppet agent runs but never changes anything. You check the master and find an unsigned certificate request. After running <code>puppetserver ca sign --certname newnode</code>, the next agent run receives its catalog and converges. The cert-signing step is the link people forget.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Unattended Deployment: Kickstart and cloud-init", body:"<p>Provisioning one server interactively is fine; provisioning fifty is not. <span class='keyterm'>Unattended deployment</span> lets a machine install and configure itself from an answer file, with no human clicking through the installer. The exam covers the major answer-file systems for each distribution family plus the cloud-image initializer, and expects you to pair the right tool with the right distro.</p><h3>Kickstart for Red Hat</h3><p>The Red Hat family uses <span class='keyterm'>Kickstart</span>. A Kickstart file (commonly <code>ks.cfg</code> or <code>anaconda-ks.cfg</code>) is a text file that answers every prompt the Anaconda installer would ask: language, keyboard, disk partitioning, network, root password, time zone, and the list of packages to install. Sections like <code>%packages</code> list software, and <code>%post</code> contains shell commands run after installation -- ideal for first-boot configuration. A fragment might read <code>lang en_US.UTF-8</code>, then <code>rootpw --iscrypted $6$...</code>, then a <code>%packages</code> block listing <code>@core</code> and <code>vim</code>. After any manual install, Anaconda writes <code>/root/anaconda-ks.cfg</code> recording the choices made, giving you a ready template to edit and reuse. Validate a file before deploying with <code>ksvalidator ks.cfg</code>.</p><h3>Preseed for Debian</h3><p>The Debian and Ubuntu family uses <span class='keyterm'>preseed</span>. A preseed file feeds answers to the debian-installer in a <code>owner question type value</code> format, for example <code>d-i passwd/root-password-crypted password $6$...</code> or a line selecting the target disk for partitioning. The file can be supplied on the install media, fetched from a URL with the <code>url=</code> boot parameter, or passed as kernel boot parameters. Preseed serves the same role as Kickstart but with different syntax and a different installer. Newer Ubuntu releases use <em>autoinstall</em> (a cloud-init-based YAML) in place of classic preseed, which is why the boundary between preseed and cloud-init has blurred on that family.</p><h3>Why Answer Files Matter</h3><p>The unifying idea behind every system in this section is the same: capture an installation's decisions once, as text, and replay them deterministically as many times as needed. That text file is itself a form of Infrastructure as Code -- it belongs in version control, can be peer-reviewed, and produces identical machines whether you build one server or a thousand. This eliminates the manual, error-prone clicking through an installer that produces subtly different snowflake systems. It also makes provisioning auditable: the answer file is a precise record of exactly how a machine was built, including its partitioning scheme, package set, and post-install steps. Treating Kickstart, preseed, and cloud-config files as version-controlled artifacts is what turns one-off installs into a repeatable, documented provisioning pipeline.</p><table><thead><tr><th>System</th><th>Family</th><th>Installer</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Kickstart</td><td>Red Hat / Fedora</td><td>Anaconda</td></tr><tr><td>Preseed</td><td>Debian / Ubuntu</td><td>debian-installer</td></tr><tr><td>AutoYaST</td><td>SUSE</td><td>YaST</td></tr><tr><td>cloud-init</td><td>Cloud images (all)</td><td>First-boot config</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>cloud-init for Cloud Images</h3><p>Cloud and virtualization platforms ship generic disk images that must self-configure on first boot. <span class='keyterm'>cloud-init</span> is the de facto standard that does this. On first boot it reads <em>user data</em> supplied by the platform -- typically a YAML file beginning with <code>#cloud-config</code> -- and applies it: setting the hostname, creating users, injecting SSH public keys, writing files, installing packages with <code>packages:</code>, and running arbitrary commands with <code>runcmd:</code>. A snippet such as <code>users:</code> followed by a name and <code>ssh_authorized_keys:</code> arrives configured with your login key, and a <code>runcmd:</code> list of <code>- [systemctl, restart, nginx]</code> runs commands at the end. cloud-init reads its data from a <em>datasource</em> appropriate to the platform (a metadata service, an attached ISO, or a config drive), and it only runs its per-instance modules on the <em>first</em> boot unless its state is cleared.</p><h3>PXE-Driven Installs</h3><p>To install across the network onto bare metal with no media, administrators combine these answer files with <span class='keyterm'>PXE</span> (Preboot Execution Environment). The target's firmware requests an address via <span class='keyterm'>DHCP</span>, downloads a bootloader and kernel over <span class='keyterm'>TFTP</span>, and the installer then fetches its Kickstart or preseed file from an HTTP server. A whole rack can be reimaged by simply network-booting each node, making PXE plus Kickstart the classic data-center provisioning pipeline. The same approach scales to disaster recovery: if a server's disk dies, you replace the hardware, network-boot it, and it reinstalls from the identical answer file with no manual installer interaction. This is the bare-metal equivalent of the immutable, reproducible infrastructure that cloud images give you through cloud-init.</p><table><thead><tr><th>PXE stage</th><th>Protocol</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Get IP + boot file location</td><td>DHCP</td></tr><tr><td>Download bootloader + kernel</td><td>TFTP</td></tr><tr><td>Fetch answer file (ks/preseed)</td><td>HTTP/FTP/NFS</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Match the answer file to the family: Kickstart equals Red Hat (Anaconda), preseed equals Debian/Ubuntu, AutoYaST equals SUSE, and cloud-init configures cloud images on first boot from <code>#cloud-config</code> user data. A leftover <code>/root/anaconda-ks.cfg</code> is your starting template on RHEL. PXE uses DHCP then TFTP.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A cloud instance launches but your SSH key is missing, locking you out. The cause is malformed YAML under <code>ssh_authorized_keys:</code> in the user data -- cloud-init silently skipped the block. Checking <code>/var/log/cloud-init.log</code> reveals the parse error; fixing the indentation and relaunching injects the key correctly.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"CI/CD and DevSecOps", body:"<p>Automation does not stop at provisioning. Modern software delivery wraps code changes in a <span class='keyterm'>pipeline</span> that builds, tests, and deploys automatically. The Linux+ exam introduces the vocabulary of continuous integration, continuous delivery, and the security practices layered on top -- enough to read a pipeline file and explain what each stage does.</p><h3>CI and CD</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Continuous Integration (CI)</span> is the practice of merging developers' changes into a shared branch frequently, with each merge automatically triggering a build and an automated test suite. The goal is to catch integration problems within minutes of a commit rather than at the end of a long cycle. <span class='keyterm'>Continuous Delivery (CD)</span> extends this so that any build passing all tests is automatically prepared for release; <span class='keyterm'>Continuous Deployment</span> goes one step further and pushes every passing build to production without a manual gate. The difference between delivery and deployment is exactly that one human approval step.</p><h3>Pipelines</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>pipeline</span> is the ordered set of automated stages a change passes through -- typically build, then unit test, then integration test, then security scan, then deploy. Pipelines are themselves defined as code, in files read by tools like GitLab CI (<code>.gitlab-ci.yml</code>), GitHub Actions (workflow YAML under <code>.github/workflows/</code>), or Jenkins (<code>Jenkinsfile</code>). A failure at any stage stops the pipeline and notifies the team, so broken code never reaches the next stage. A minimal GitLab pipeline is just a few YAML lines:</p><pre><code>stages:\n  - build\n  - test\nbuild-job:\n  stage: build\n  script:\n    - make build\ntest-job:\n  stage: test\n  script:\n    - make test</code></pre><h3>Shift-Left and DevSecOps</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Shift-left testing</span> means moving testing -- including security testing -- as early as possible in the pipeline, ideally at commit time, rather than treating it as a final gate. Catching a vulnerability the moment code is written is far cheaper than after deployment. <span class='keyterm'>DevSecOps</span> is the cultural and tooling practice of embedding security into every stage of the DevOps pipeline rather than bolting it on at the end: automated dependency scanning, static analysis (SAST), dynamic analysis (DAST), container image scanning, and secrets detection all run as pipeline stages. Security becomes a shared, automated responsibility instead of a separate team's late-stage review.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>CI</td><td>Frequent merges trigger auto build + test</td></tr><tr><td>Continuous Delivery</td><td>Passing builds auto-prepared (manual deploy)</td></tr><tr><td>Continuous Deployment</td><td>Passing builds auto-deployed (no gate)</td></tr><tr><td>Pipeline</td><td>Ordered automated stages for a change</td></tr><tr><td>Shift-left</td><td>Test/scan early, at commit time</td></tr><tr><td>DevSecOps</td><td>Security embedded throughout the pipeline</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>File Types in IaC and Pipelines</h3><p>Three text formats dominate this world, and the exam expects you to recognize them on sight. <span class='keyterm'>YAML</span> uses indentation and <code>key: value</code> pairs, is highly readable, and is the language of Ansible playbooks, Kubernetes manifests, and most CI pipeline definitions. <span class='keyterm'>JSON</span> uses braces and brackets, is stricter and more verbose, and is common for APIs, cloud templates, and machine-to-machine data. <span class='keyterm'>HCL</span> (HashiCorp Configuration Language) is purpose-built for Terraform and OpenTofu <code>.tf</code> files. All three are plain text, so all three live in Git.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Format</th><th>Style</th><th>Typical use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>YAML</td><td>Indentation, <code>key: value</code></td><td>Ansible, Kubernetes, CI</td></tr><tr><td>JSON</td><td>Braces and brackets</td><td>APIs, cloud templates</td></tr><tr><td>HCL</td><td>Blocks with <code>=</code></td><td>Terraform / OpenTofu</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Git-Driven Workflows and GitOps</h3><p>Because pipelines and infrastructure are now code, Git becomes the trigger for everything. A push to a branch starts the relevant pipeline automatically. <span class='keyterm'>GitOps</span> takes this to its conclusion: the Git repository is the single source of truth for the desired state of infrastructure, and an automated agent continuously reconciles the running environment to match what is committed. A change is made by merging a pull request, and the system converges -- no one runs deploy commands by hand. The audit trail is simply the Git history. Reverting a bad change becomes as simple as reverting a commit, and the reconciliation agent rolls the environment back automatically. This closes the loop between version control, automation, and orchestration that the whole domain has been building toward.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Recognize the three IaC file formats: YAML (indentation, Ansible/Kubernetes/CI), JSON (braces, APIs/cloud templates), HCL (Terraform/OpenTofu). Shift-left means test early; DevSecOps means security is automated into every pipeline stage. Continuous Deployment removes the manual approval that Continuous Delivery keeps.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A vulnerable dependency reaches production and triggers an incident. The team adds a SAST and dependency-scan stage early in the pipeline so future builds fail fast on known CVEs -- a textbook shift-left fix that catches the issue at commit time rather than in production.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Container Orchestration: Kubernetes and Docker Swarm", body:"<p>Running a handful of containers on one host is easy; running hundreds across a cluster with self-healing, scaling, and networking requires a <span class='keyterm'>container orchestrator</span>. Linux+ covers Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, and the Compose tooling used for local multi-container definitions, and expects you to know each one's scope and core objects.</p><h3>Kubernetes</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Kubernetes</span> (often abbreviated <em>k8s</em>) is the dominant orchestrator. Its smallest deployable unit is the <span class='keyterm'>pod</span>, a wrapper around one or more tightly coupled containers that share a network namespace and storage. Pods are ephemeral and may be rescheduled, so you do not address them directly; instead a <span class='keyterm'>service</span> provides a stable virtual IP and DNS name that load-balances across the pods backing it. Higher-level objects like <em>Deployments</em> manage replica counts and rolling updates. Configuration is injected into pods through <span class='keyterm'>environment variables</span>, <span class='keyterm'>ConfigMaps</span> (non-secret config), and <span class='keyterm'>Secrets</span> (sensitive values), keeping config out of the image.</p><p>You declare all of this in YAML manifests and apply them with <code>kubectl apply -f deployment.yml</code>, then inspect with <code>kubectl get pods</code> and <code>kubectl get services</code>. Common verbs include <code>kubectl describe pod web-xyz</code> for detail, <code>kubectl logs web-xyz</code> for container output, and <code>kubectl scale deployment web --replicas=5</code> to change the replica count on the fly.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Kubernetes object</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Pod</td><td>Smallest unit; one or more containers</td></tr><tr><td>Service</td><td>Stable IP/DNS load-balancing to pods</td></tr><tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Manages replicas and rolling updates</td></tr><tr><td>ConfigMap</td><td>Non-secret configuration data</td></tr><tr><td>Secret</td><td>Sensitive values (base64, restricted)</td></tr><tr><td>Namespace</td><td>Logical partition of cluster objects</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Docker Swarm</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Docker Swarm</span> is Docker's built-in, simpler orchestrator. A swarm is a cluster of Docker <span class='keyterm'>nodes</span> -- <em>managers</em> that maintain cluster state and schedule work, and <em>workers</em> that run the containers. You initialize a cluster with <code>docker swarm init</code>, join nodes with the printed <code>docker swarm join</code> token, and deploy a <span class='keyterm'>service</span> (the desired state for a set of replicated container tasks) with <code>docker service create --replicas 3 nginx</code>. Swarm spreads the replicas across nodes and reschedules them if a node fails. It provides built-in <span class='keyterm'>overlay networks</span> that let containers on different hosts communicate as if on one network, plus an internal load balancer. Swarm is easier to stand up than Kubernetes but far less feature-rich, so it suits smaller deployments.</p><h3>Compose Files</h3><p>For defining and running a multi-container application on a single host, <span class='keyterm'>Docker Compose</span> (and the compatible <span class='keyterm'>Podman Compose</span>) reads a YAML <span class='keyterm'>compose file</span> -- by convention <code>compose.yaml</code> or <code>docker-compose.yml</code>. It declares <em>services</em> (each a container with its image, ports, volumes, and environment), networks, and volumes in one file:</p><pre><code>services:\n  web:\n    image: nginx\n    ports:\n      - '8080:80'\n  db:\n    image: postgres\n    environment:\n      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: secret</code></pre><p>The command <code>docker compose up -d</code> brings the whole stack online in the background, and <code>docker compose down</code> tears it down. Compose is for development and single-host deployment; the same file concepts inform how you think about Swarm stacks (<code>docker stack deploy</code>).</p><h3>Choosing an Orchestrator</h3><p>The decision among these three comes down to scale and complexity. <span class='keyterm'>Compose</span> is the right tool when everything runs on one machine and you simply want to bring several related containers up and down together -- a developer laptop or a small single-server app. <span class='keyterm'>Docker Swarm</span> steps up to multiple hosts with minimal added complexity, giving you replicas, failover, and overlay networking without a steep learning curve, which suits small clusters. <span class='keyterm'>Kubernetes</span> is the heavyweight: it adds self-healing, automated rollouts and rollbacks, horizontal autoscaling, rich networking, and a vast ecosystem, at the cost of significant operational complexity. The industry has largely standardized on Kubernetes for production at scale, while Compose remains ubiquitous for local development.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Scope</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Kubernetes</td><td>Large multi-host clusters, rich features</td></tr><tr><td>Docker Swarm</td><td>Simpler multi-host clusters</td></tr><tr><td>Compose</td><td>Multi-container app on one host</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The Kubernetes pod is the smallest deployable unit, and a service gives pods a stable address. ConfigMaps hold non-secret config, Secrets hold sensitive data. In Swarm you create a <em>service</em> with replicas across manager and worker nodes. Compose files (<code>compose.yaml</code>) define multi-container apps for a single host. The kubectl verb to deploy is <code>apply -f</code>.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A pod keeps restarting with <em>CrashLoopBackOff</em>. <code>kubectl logs</code> shows it cannot find a database password. The config was hard-coded as a missing env var; moving the credential into a <code>Secret</code> and referencing it from the pod spec resolves the crash and keeps the value out of the image.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Bash Scripting Fundamentals: Shebang, Variables, and Quoting", body:"<p>Shell scripting is the glue of Linux administration, and Bash is its lingua franca. A solid grasp of the basics -- how a script is invoked, how variables work, and how quoting changes meaning -- prevents the subtle bugs that plague beginner scripts.</p><h3>The Shebang</h3><p>The first line of a script is the <span class='keyterm'>shebang</span>: <code>#!/bin/bash</code>. The two characters <code>#!</code> tell the kernel which interpreter should run the file. <code>#!/bin/bash</code> runs Bash specifically; <code>#!/bin/sh</code> requests a POSIX shell, which on many systems is a leaner shell lacking Bash extensions; <code>#!/usr/bin/env python3</code> finds Python via the PATH. The shebang only matters when the script is executed directly (after <code>chmod +x script.sh</code> and running <code>./script.sh</code>); it is ignored if you run <code>bash script.sh</code> explicitly, because then you have already named the interpreter.</p><h3>Variables and the No-Spaces Rule</h3><p>You assign a variable with <code>name=value</code> and -- critically -- <span class='keyterm'>there must be no spaces around the equals sign</span>. Writing <code>name = value</code> makes Bash try to run a command called <code>name</code>, a classic beginner error. You read a variable by prefixing a dollar sign: <code>echo $name</code> or, more safely, <code>echo ${name}</code> with braces to mark the boundary -- needed when text follows, as in <code>${name}_backup</code>. Variable names are case-sensitive; convention reserves UPPERCASE for environment variables and constants. To make a variable available to child processes, <code>export</code> it.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Syntax</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>name=value</code></td><td>Assign (no spaces around =)</td></tr><tr><td><code>$name</code> / <code>${name}</code></td><td>Read the value</td></tr><tr><td><code>export NAME</code></td><td>Pass to child processes</td></tr><tr><td><code>readonly NAME</code></td><td>Make a constant</td></tr><tr><td><code>unset NAME</code></td><td>Remove the variable</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Quoting: Single versus Double</h3><p>Quoting controls how Bash expands what is inside. <span class='keyterm'>Single quotes</span> are literal -- nothing inside is interpreted, so <code>echo '$HOME costs $5'</code> prints the text exactly. <span class='keyterm'>Double quotes</span> allow variable and command expansion but suppress word-splitting and globbing, so <code>echo 'Home is '$HOME</code> substitutes the value while keeping spaces intact. The rule of thumb: use double quotes around variable references almost always, because an unquoted <code>$var</code> containing spaces will split into multiple arguments and break your script. Use single quotes when you want the text untouched.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Quote</th><th>Variable expansion?</th><th>Use when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Single <code>' '</code></td><td>No -- fully literal</td><td>Text must stay exact</td></tr><tr><td>Double <code>&quot; &quot;</code></td><td>Yes, but no word-split</td><td>Around variables (default)</td></tr><tr><td>None</td><td>Yes + word-split + glob</td><td>Rarely -- risky</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Command Substitution</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Command substitution</span> captures the output of a command into your script. The modern form is <code>$(command)</code>; the older backtick form works but does not nest cleanly. For example, <code>today=$(date +%F)</code> stores the current date, and <code>count=$(ls | wc -l)</code> stores a file count. Always prefer <code>$(...)</code> over backticks because it nests and reads more clearly.</p><h3>Positional Parameters</h3><p>Arguments passed to a script become <span class='keyterm'>positional parameters</span>. <code>$1</code> is the first argument, <code>$2</code> the second, and so on; <code>$0</code> is the script's own name. <code>$#</code> is the count of arguments, useful for validating input. <code>$@</code> expands to all arguments as separate quoted words (use it quoted), while <code>$*</code> joins them into one string. So a script invoked as <code>./backup.sh /etc nightly</code> sees <code>$1</code> as <code>/etc</code>, <code>$2</code> as <code>nightly</code>, and <code>$#</code> as 2. Beyond these, <code>$$</code> holds the script's own process ID (useful for unique temp-file names like <code>/tmp/work.$$</code>), and the <code>shift</code> builtin discards <code>$1</code> and renumbers the rest down, the standard way to walk through a variable-length argument list one at a time.</p><h3>Environment versus Shell Variables</h3><p>It helps to distinguish a plain <span class='keyterm'>shell variable</span>, which exists only in the current shell, from an <span class='keyterm'>environment variable</span>, which is copied into every child process you launch. Assigning <code>FOO=bar</code> creates a shell variable; <code>export FOO</code> promotes it to the environment so a script or program you run can read it. Running <code>env</code> or <code>printenv</code> lists the current environment, and <code>FOO=bar somecommand</code> sets a variable for just that one command's invocation without affecting the rest of the shell. Several names are special by convention: <code>PATH</code> lists directories searched for commands, <code>HOME</code> is your home directory, and <code>PWD</code> is the current working directory.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Two facts get tested constantly: assignment takes <em>no spaces</em> around <code>=</code>, and single quotes are literal while double quotes expand variables. Memorize the positional parameters: <code>$0</code> script name, <code>$1</code>..<code>$9</code> args, <code>$#</code> arg count, all-args-as-separate-words via quoted <code>$@</code>. Use <code>$(...)</code> for command substitution.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A backup script fails on a directory named <code>My Files</code>. The culprit is an unquoted <code>$dir</code>: word-splitting turned one path into two arguments. Wrapping the variable in double quotes everywhere it is used fixes the script for paths containing spaces.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Expansion and Substitution", body:"<p>Before Bash runs a command it performs several rounds of <span class='keyterm'>expansion</span>, transforming the text you typed into the final arguments. Understanding these expansions lets you write concise, powerful scripts and avoid surprises about what actually reaches a command.</p><h3>Parameter Expansion</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Parameter expansion</span> is the family of operations on variables written with braces. Beyond plain <code>${var}</code>, Bash offers defaults, length, and substrings. <code>${var:-default}</code> yields <code>default</code> if <code>var</code> is unset or empty, leaving <code>var</code> unchanged -- ideal for fallback values. <code>${var:=default}</code> also assigns the default. <code>${#var}</code> gives the length of the value. Substring extraction uses <code>${var:offset:length}</code>, so if <code>name=admin</code> then <code>${name:0:3}</code> is <code>adm</code>. Pattern removal trims prefixes and suffixes: <code>${file%.txt}</code> strips a trailing <code>.txt</code>, and <code>${path##*/}</code> yields the basename by removing the longest leading match up to the last slash.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Expansion</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>${var:-def}</code></td><td>Use def if var unset/empty</td></tr><tr><td><code>${var:=def}</code></td><td>Assign def if var unset/empty</td></tr><tr><td><code>${var:?msg}</code></td><td>Error and exit if var unset</td></tr><tr><td><code>${#var}</code></td><td>Length of var's value</td></tr><tr><td><code>${var:2:3}</code></td><td>Substring, offset 2, length 3</td></tr><tr><td><code>${var%suffix}</code></td><td>Remove shortest trailing match</td></tr><tr><td><code>${var##prefix}</code></td><td>Remove longest leading match</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Command and Arithmetic Expansion</h3><p>As covered earlier, <code>$(command)</code> replaces itself with the command's standard output, with trailing newlines trimmed. It can be nested -- <code>$(dirname $(readlink -f script.sh))</code> -- which is why it is preferred over backticks. Bash also does integer math inside <code>$((...))</code>. <code>echo $((3 + 4))</code> prints 7, and <code>count=$((count + 1))</code> increments a counter. Inside the double parentheses you do not need dollar signs on variable names, so <code>$((i * 2))</code> works. Comparison operators inside <code>(( ))</code> return success or failure, which is handy in loops: <code>(( i &lt; 10 ))</code>. Note that Bash arithmetic is integer-only; for floating point you reach for <code>bc</code> or <code>awk</code>, as in <code>echo 'scale=2; 7/2' | bc</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Construct</th><th>Does</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>$(cmd)</code></td><td>Capture command output</td></tr><tr><td><code>$((expr))</code></td><td>Integer arithmetic (returns value)</td></tr><tr><td><code>((expr))</code></td><td>Arithmetic test (returns status)</td></tr><tr><td><code>$(($a + $b))</code></td><td>Sum (no $ needed inside)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Brace, Tilde, and Glob Expansion</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>Brace expansion</span> generates lists: <code>echo file{1,2,3}.txt</code> produces three filenames, and <code>mkdir /srv/{web,db,cache}</code> makes three directories at once. Ranges work too: <code>{1..5}</code> expands to <code>1 2 3 4 5</code> and <code>{a..e}</code> to letters. <span class='keyterm'>Tilde expansion</span> turns <code>~</code> into your home directory and <code>~user</code> into that user's home. <span class='keyterm'>Glob</span> (pathname) expansion turns wildcards into matching filenames: <code>*</code> matches any characters, <code>?</code> a single character, and <code>[a-z]</code> a character range, so <code>ls *.log</code> lists every log file. Brace expansion happens before glob and works even when no files match, whereas a glob that matches nothing is left literal by default (unless <code>nullglob</code> is set).</p><h3>Subshells</h3><p>Wrapping commands in parentheses runs them in a <span class='keyterm'>subshell</span> -- a child process with its own copy of the environment. <code>(cd /tmp &amp;&amp; tar czf /backup/t.tgz .)</code> changes directory only inside the subshell, so your script's working directory is unaffected afterward. Variables set in a subshell do not propagate back to the parent, which is the key behavioral difference from grouping with braces <code>{ ...; }</code>, which runs in the current shell and <em>does</em> affect it. A common gotcha: a <code>while read</code> loop fed by a pipe runs in a subshell, so counters incremented inside it are lost after the loop ends.</p><h3>The Order of Expansions</h3><p>Bash applies its expansions in a fixed, defined order, and knowing it explains otherwise baffling behavior. Brace expansion happens first, then tilde expansion, then parameter and arithmetic and command substitution (all together, left to right), then word splitting on <code>IFS</code>, and finally pathname (glob) expansion. Because word splitting comes <em>after</em> variable expansion, an unquoted variable that contains spaces is split into multiple words at that stage -- which is precisely why quoting variable references matters so much. Because brace expansion comes first and is purely textual, <code>echo {1..3}</code> produces <code>1 2 3</code> even when no such files exist, whereas a glob like <code>*.none</code> that matches nothing is normally left untouched. Quoting suppresses the later stages: putting double quotes around an expansion blocks word splitting and globbing while still allowing the variable or command substitution to occur.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Know the difference between <code>$(( ))</code> for arithmetic and <code>$( )</code> for command substitution -- the extra parenthesis matters. <code>${var:-default}</code> provides a fallback without assigning; <code>${#var}</code> is length. A subshell <code>( )</code> isolates directory changes and variable assignments from the parent; braces <code>{ }</code> do not.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A script sums file sizes inside <code>cat list | while read f; do total=$((total+sz)); done</code> but <code>total</code> is empty afterward. The pipe ran the loop in a subshell. Switching to <code>while read f; do ...; done &lt; list</code> (redirect, no pipe) keeps the loop in the current shell and preserves <code>total</code>.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Conditionals and Test Constructs", body:"<p>Scripts make decisions with conditionals. Bash offers a family of test constructs whose differences trip up the unwary, so the exam probes whether you know when to use <code>test</code>, single brackets, or double brackets, and which operators belong with strings versus numbers.</p><h3>The if Statement</h3><p>The basic form is <code>if condition; then ...; elif other; then ...; else ...; fi</code>. The <span class='keyterm'>condition</span> is itself a command, and the branch runs if that command's exit status is zero (success). This is why <code>if grep -q root /etc/passwd; then ...</code> works without any brackets -- it tests grep's exit code directly. The block is closed with <code>fi</code> (if reversed), and <code>elif</code> chains additional tests. Indentation is conventional, not required.</p><h3>test, [ ], and [[ ]]</h3><p>The classic test command exists in two spellings: <code>test EXPRESSION</code> and the equivalent <code>[ EXPRESSION ]</code>, where <code>[</code> is literally a command and therefore <span class='keyterm'>requires spaces inside the brackets</span> and a closing <code>]</code>. Bash adds an enhanced keyword form, <code>[[ EXPRESSION ]]</code>, which is safer: it does not perform word-splitting or globbing on its operands, so unquoted variables are less dangerous, and it supports <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, <code>||</code>, and pattern matching directly. Prefer <code>[[ ]]</code> in Bash scripts; use <code>[ ]</code> only when you need POSIX portability under <code>/bin/sh</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Construct</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>test expr</code></td><td>Original test command</td></tr><tr><td><code>[ expr ]</code></td><td>Same as test; needs spaces and ]</td></tr><tr><td><code>[[ expr ]]</code></td><td>Bash keyword; safer, supports &amp;&amp; ||</td></tr><tr><td><code>(( expr ))</code></td><td>Arithmetic test (numeric)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>File Test Operators</h3><p>A large set of unary operators inspects files. <code>-e</code> is true if the path exists, <code>-f</code> if it is a regular file, <code>-d</code> if it is a directory, and <code>-L</code> if it is a symlink. Permission tests include <code>-r</code> (readable), <code>-w</code> (writable), and <code>-x</code> (executable). Size and emptiness use <code>-s</code> (file exists and is non-empty). So <code>if [[ -f /etc/hosts ]]; then ...</code> guards against acting on a missing file, and <code>if [[ -d $dir ]]; then ...</code> confirms a directory before using it. You can negate any test with <code>!</code>, as in <code>if [[ ! -e /tmp/lock ]]; then ...</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operator</th><th>True when</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>-e path</code></td><td>Path exists</td></tr><tr><td><code>-f path</code></td><td>Regular file</td></tr><tr><td><code>-d path</code></td><td>Directory</td></tr><tr><td><code>-L path</code></td><td>Symbolic link</td></tr><tr><td><code>-r/-w/-x</code></td><td>Readable / writable / executable</td></tr><tr><td><code>-s path</code></td><td>Exists and is non-empty</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>String and Numeric Comparisons</h3><p>Strings and numbers use different operators, and confusing them is a frequent bug. <span class='keyterm'>Strings</span> compare with <code>=</code> (or <code>==</code> inside <code>[[ ]]</code>) and <code>!=</code>, with <code>-z</code> true for an empty string and <code>-n</code> true for a non-empty one. <span class='keyterm'>Numbers</span> use the two-letter operators <code>-eq</code> (equal), <code>-ne</code> (not equal), <code>-lt</code> (less than), <code>-le</code>, <code>-gt</code>, and <code>-ge</code>. So <code>[[ $name = admin ]]</code> compares text, while <code>[[ $count -gt 10 ]]</code> compares integers. Using <code>=</code> on numbers or <code>-eq</code> on strings is a classic error -- <code>[[ 10 = 010 ]]</code> is false as strings but <code>[[ 10 -eq 010 ]]</code> is true as numbers.</p><h3>The case Statement</h3><p>When testing one value against many patterns, <span class='keyterm'>case</span> is cleaner than a long if/elif chain. Its form is <code>case $1 in</code> followed by pattern blocks like <code>start) ...;;</code> and <code>stop) ...;;</code>, a catch-all <code>*) ...;;</code>, and a closing <code>esac</code> (case reversed). Each pattern supports globbing, so <code>*.txt)</code> matches any text file, and the double semicolon <code>;;</code> ends each branch. This is exactly how init scripts dispatch on <code>start</code>, <code>stop</code>, and <code>restart</code>. Multiple patterns can share a branch by separating them with a pipe, as in <code>start|begin)</code>, and because patterns are matched top to bottom the catch-all <code>*)</code> must always come last.</p><h3>Combining Conditions</h3><p>Real conditions often test more than one thing at once. Inside <code>[[ ]]</code> you join tests with <code>&amp;&amp;</code> (logical AND) and <code>||</code> (logical OR) directly: <code>if [[ -f $file &amp;&amp; -r $file ]]; then ...</code> proceeds only when the path is both a regular file and readable. You can also chain whole commands at the statement level the same way -- <code>command1 &amp;&amp; command2</code> runs the second only if the first succeeded. Parentheses group sub-expressions when precedence matters, and a leading <code>!</code> negates: <code>if [[ ! -d /backup ]]; then mkdir /backup; fi</code> creates the directory only if it does not already exist. Older single-bracket syntax uses the clumsier <code>-a</code> and <code>-o</code> operators for AND and OR, another reason to prefer <code>[[ ]]</code> in Bash.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>String equality is <code>=</code>; numeric equality is <code>-eq</code>. <code>-f</code> tests a regular file, <code>-d</code> a directory, <code>-e</code> existence. <code>[ ]</code> needs spaces inside; <code>[[ ]]</code> is the safer Bash form. <code>case</code> ends with <code>esac</code> and each branch ends with <code>;;</code>.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A check <code>if [ $reply == y ]; then</code> errors with <em>too many arguments</em> when <code>reply</code> is empty, because the single-bracket test sees a missing operand. Switching to <code>[[ $reply == y ]]</code> (which does not word-split) and quoting habits eliminates the whole class of empty-variable test failures.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Loops and Functions", body:"<p>Loops repeat work and functions package it for reuse. Together they turn flat scripts into structured programs, and the exam expects fluency with all three loop forms plus function definition and scope.</p><h3>The for Loop</h3><p>The <span class='keyterm'>for</span> loop iterates over a list of words. <code>for f in *.log; do gzip $f; done</code> compresses every log file; the loop body runs once per item with <code>f</code> set to each value. You can iterate a brace range, <code>for i in {1..5}</code>, or a command's output, <code>for u in $(cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd)</code>. Bash also supports a C-style form, <code>for (( i=0; i&lt;10; i++ )); do ...; done</code>, useful when you need a numeric counter. Always quote the loop variable in the body when it may contain spaces.</p><h3>while and until</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>while</span> loop runs its body as long as a condition stays true: <code>while [[ $count -lt 10 ]]; do ...; count=$((count+1)); done</code>. An <span class='keyterm'>until</span> loop is its mirror image, running until the condition becomes true -- handy for waiting on something, as in <code>until ping -c1 host; do sleep 5; done</code>. Both close with <code>done</code>. Forgetting to advance the counter inside a <code>while</code> is the classic cause of an infinite loop.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Loop</th><th>Runs while...</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>for x in list</code></td><td>items remain in the list</td></tr><tr><td><code>while cond</code></td><td>condition is true</td></tr><tr><td><code>until cond</code></td><td>condition is false (until true)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>break, continue, and Reading Input</h3><p>Inside any loop, <span class='keyterm'>break</span> exits the loop entirely and <span class='keyterm'>continue</span> skips to the next iteration. They let you short-circuit: <code>break</code> when you have found what you need, or <code>continue</code> to skip items that fail a test. The <span class='keyterm'>read</span> builtin pulls a line of input into variables. <code>read -p 'Name: ' name</code> prompts and stores the reply. The canonical pattern for processing a file or command output line by line is <code>while read -r line; do ...; done &lt; file.txt</code>, where <code>-r</code> prevents backslash mangling. To split each line into fields you list multiple variables: <code>while IFS=: read -r user pass uid rest; do ...; done &lt; /etc/passwd</code>. The <span class='keyterm'>IFS</span> (Internal Field Separator) variable controls how lines are split into words; setting <code>IFS=:</code> for that read makes it split on colons -- the standard way to parse <code>/etc/passwd</code>.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Keyword</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>break</code></td><td>Exit the loop entirely</td></tr><tr><td><code>continue</code></td><td>Skip to the next iteration</td></tr><tr><td><code>read -r line</code></td><td>Read one line (no backslash escapes)</td></tr><tr><td><code>IFS=:</code></td><td>Split fields on a colon</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Functions</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>function</span> groups commands under a name. Define it as <code>greet() { echo 'Hello '$1; }</code> and call it like a command, <code>greet world</code>. Inside a function the positional parameters <code>$1</code>, <code>$2</code>, <code>$@</code> refer to the function's own arguments, not the script's. A function communicates a result two ways: it <em>returns</em> an exit status (0-255) with <code>return</code>, tested by the caller via <code>$?</code>, and it can print a value to stdout that the caller captures with command substitution, <code>result=$(myfunc)</code>. By default all variables are global; declare <span class='keyterm'>local</span> variables with <code>local tmp=...</code> so they do not leak out and clobber the caller's variables -- a discipline that prevents maddening bugs in larger scripts. Functions must be defined before they are called, since Bash reads the script top to bottom, so the convention is to declare all functions near the top and put the main logic at the bottom.</p><h3>Nesting and Loop Control Depth</h3><p>Loops and conditionals nest freely, and the exam may show a loop containing an <code>if</code> containing another loop. When loops are nested, <code>break</code> and <code>continue</code> accept an optional numeric argument naming how many levels to act on: <code>break 2</code> exits two enclosing loops at once, and <code>continue 2</code> jumps to the next iteration of the loop two levels out. This avoids awkward flag variables when an inner loop needs to abandon the entire outer structure. A frequent real-world pattern is a <code>for</code> loop over hosts wrapping a <code>while read</code> loop over each host's config lines; getting the <code>break</code> level right is what makes such a script behave. Combined with <code>local</code> variables inside functions, these controls let you build sizable, maintainable programs entirely in Bash before reaching for Python.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>name() { ...; }</code></td><td>Define a function</td></tr><tr><td><code>return N</code></td><td>Set exit status (0-255)</td></tr><tr><td><code>local var</code></td><td>Scope a variable to the function</td></tr><tr><td><code>$1 $@</code></td><td>Function's own arguments</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The line-reading idiom is <code>while read -r line; do ...; done &lt; file</code>. <code>IFS</code> sets the field separator for splitting. A function's <code>return</code> sets an exit status (0-255), not a string -- to pass data back, echo it and capture with <code>$()</code>. Use <code>local</code> so function variables do not leak.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A function tries <code>return 'web1'</code> and the script breaks. <code>return</code> only sets a 0-255 status, so the string is invalid. Rewriting the function to <code>echo</code> the hostname and capturing it with <code>host=$(get_host)</code> passes the value back correctly.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Exit Codes, Operators, and Regular Expressions", body:"<p>Robust scripts react to success and failure, chain commands intelligently, and match text patterns. These mechanics -- exit codes, logical operators, and regular expressions -- separate fragile one-liners from production-grade automation.</p><h3>Exit Status and $?</h3><p>Every command returns an <span class='keyterm'>exit status</span>: a number from 0 to 255 where <span class='keyterm'>0 means success</span> and any non-zero value means failure. The special variable <code>$?</code> holds the status of the most recently completed command, so <code>cp a b; echo $?</code> prints 0 if the copy worked. Inside a function or script, <code>exit N</code> sets the script's own status. By convention specific non-zero codes signal specific failures (1 general error, 2 misuse, 126 not executable, 127 command not found, 130 terminated by Ctrl-C), letting callers and pipelines react precisely.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>0</td><td>Success</td></tr><tr><td>1</td><td>General error</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Misuse of builtin</td></tr><tr><td>126</td><td>Found but not executable</td></tr><tr><td>127</td><td>Command not found</td></tr><tr><td>130</td><td>Terminated by Ctrl-C (SIGINT)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Logical Operators</h3><p>The operators <span class='keyterm'>&amp;&amp;</span> and <span class='keyterm'>||</span> chain commands based on exit status. <code>cmd1 &amp;&amp; cmd2</code> runs <code>cmd2</code> only if <code>cmd1</code> succeeded; <code>cmd1 || cmd2</code> runs <code>cmd2</code> only if <code>cmd1</code> failed. This gives terse, readable guards: <code>mkdir /data &amp;&amp; cd /data</code> proceeds only on success, while <code>ping -c1 host || echo 'host down'</code> reports a failure. The semicolon <code>;</code> by contrast simply separates commands and runs them unconditionally.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Operator</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>&amp;&amp;</code></td><td>Run next only if previous succeeded</td></tr><tr><td><code>||</code></td><td>Run next only if previous failed</td></tr><tr><td><code>;</code></td><td>Run next regardless</td></tr><tr><td><code>$?</code></td><td>Exit status of last command</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Defensive Options: set -e and friends</h3><p>By default a script keeps running after a command fails, which can be dangerous. <code>set -e</code> makes the script exit immediately if any command returns non-zero, stopping a cascade of errors. <code>set -u</code> treats use of an unset variable as an error, catching typos. <code>set -o pipefail</code> makes a pipeline fail if any stage fails, not just the last. <code>set -x</code> echoes each command before running it, invaluable for debugging. The combined <code>set -euo pipefail</code> near the top of a script is a widely recommended safety harness.</p><h3>Regular Expressions in Scripts</h3><p>Bash can match a string against a <span class='keyterm'>regular expression</span> with the <code>=~</code> operator inside <code>[[ ]]</code>: <code>if [[ $ip =~ ^[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+ ]]; then ...</code> tests a rough IP shape. More commonly you reach for the classic text tools. <span class='keyterm'>grep</span> filters lines that match a pattern -- <code>grep -E '^error' log</code> with <code>-E</code> for extended regex. <span class='keyterm'>sed</span> performs stream edits, most often substitution: <code>sed 's/old/new/g' file</code> replaces every occurrence. <span class='keyterm'>awk</span> is a field-oriented language ideal for columnar data: <code>awk '{print $1, $3}' file</code> prints the first and third whitespace-separated fields, and <code>awk -F: '$3 &gt;= 1000 {print $1}' /etc/passwd</code> lists regular users by testing the UID field. Anchors (<code>^</code> start, <code>$</code> end), character classes (<code>[0-9]</code>), and quantifiers (<code>*</code>, <code>+</code>, <code>?</code>) are the regex building blocks shared across all three.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Job</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>grep</code></td><td>Filter lines matching a pattern</td></tr><tr><td><code>sed</code></td><td>Stream edit / substitute</td></tr><tr><td><code>awk</code></td><td>Field-oriented processing</td></tr><tr><td><code>=~</code></td><td>Regex match inside <code>[[ ]]</code></td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Best Practices</h3><p>Production scripts share habits worth memorizing: start with an explicit <code>#!/bin/bash</code> shebang, add comments explaining intent, quote every variable expansion, enable <code>set -euo pipefail</code>, check exit codes and validate arguments (<code>[[ $# -lt 1 ]] &amp;&amp; { echo 'usage'; exit 1; }</code>), and provide clear error messages on stderr with <code>echo 'error' &gt;&amp;2</code>. These practices turn a brittle script into one safe to run unattended.</p><h3>Redirection and Streams</h3><p>Closely tied to exit codes is the handling of a command's three standard streams: <span class='keyterm'>stdin</span> (file descriptor 0), <span class='keyterm'>stdout</span> (1), and <span class='keyterm'>stderr</span> (2). Redirect stdout to a file with <code>cmd &gt; out.log</code> (truncating) or <code>cmd &gt;&gt; out.log</code> (appending). Redirect stderr separately with <code>cmd 2&gt; err.log</code>, and merge stderr into stdout with the idiom <code>cmd &gt; all.log 2&gt;&amp;1</code> -- order matters, because <code>2&gt;&amp;1</code> means 'send fd 2 wherever fd 1 currently points.' To discard output entirely, redirect to <code>/dev/null</code>, as in <code>cmd 2&gt; /dev/null</code> to silence only errors. A pipe <code>cmd1 | cmd2</code> connects the stdout of the first to the stdin of the second, and keeping error output on stderr lets you pipe clean data while still seeing diagnostics. Understanding these streams is what makes <code>set -o pipefail</code> meaningful and lets scripts log cleanly.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Exit code 0 is success; <code>$?</code> holds the last status. <code>&amp;&amp;</code> chains on success, <code>||</code> on failure. <code>set -e</code> exits on the first error. The regex match operator is <code>=~</code> inside <code>[[ ]]</code>; grep filters, sed substitutes, awk works on fields.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A deploy script keeps charging ahead after a failed <code>tar</code>, corrupting the target. Adding <code>set -euo pipefail</code> at the top makes the script abort the instant <code>tar</code> returns non-zero, and <code>set -o pipefail</code> ensures a failure midway through a pipe is not masked by a successful final stage.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Python Basics for Linux Administration", body:"<p>When a task outgrows Bash -- complex data handling, API calls, structured parsing -- administrators reach for <span class='keyterm'>Python</span>. Linux+ covers enough Python to read and run admin scripts, manage environments, and recognize the core language elements.</p><h3>Running Python</h3><p>Modern systems ship <span class='keyterm'>Python 3</span>, invoked as <code>python3</code> (the bare <code>python</code> may be absent or aliased). Run a script with <code>python3 script.py</code>, or make it directly executable with the shebang <code>#!/usr/bin/env python3</code> and <code>chmod +x</code>. An interactive REPL starts by typing <code>python3</code> alone, useful for quick experiments. Check the version with <code>python3 --version</code>.</p><h3>Virtual Environments</h3><p>Installing packages system-wide risks breaking tools that depend on specific versions. A <span class='keyterm'>virtual environment</span> is an isolated, project-local Python with its own package set. Create one with <code>python3 -m venv myenv</code>, activate it with <code>source myenv/bin/activate</code> (your prompt changes to show the env name), and deactivate with <code>deactivate</code>. Inside the active venv, installs stay local and do not touch the system Python -- the standard way to keep projects from colliding. Many distributions now mark the system Python as <em>externally managed</em>, making a venv effectively mandatory for <code>pip</code>.</p><h3>pip and Dependencies</h3><p><span class='keyterm'>pip</span> is Python's package installer, pulling from the PyPI repository. <code>pip install requests</code> adds a library; <code>pip install -r requirements.txt</code> installs a pinned list of dependencies, and <code>pip freeze &gt; requirements.txt</code> records exactly what is installed so the environment is reproducible. Pinning versions in <code>requirements.txt</code> is how teams guarantee everyone runs the same dependency set.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>python3 -m venv env</code></td><td>Create a virtual environment</td></tr><tr><td><code>source env/bin/activate</code></td><td>Activate the environment</td></tr><tr><td><code>pip install pkg</code></td><td>Install a package</td></tr><tr><td><code>pip install -r requirements.txt</code></td><td>Install pinned dependencies</td></tr><tr><td><code>pip freeze</code></td><td>List installed versions</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Indentation and Data Types</h3><p>Unlike Bash, Python uses <span class='keyterm'>indentation</span> -- not braces or keywords -- to define blocks. The body of an <code>if</code>, loop, or function is the consistently indented lines beneath it, conventionally four spaces; mixing tabs and spaces is a syntax error (<code>IndentationError</code> or <code>TabError</code>). Core <span class='keyterm'>data types</span> include <code>int</code> (whole numbers), <code>float</code>, <code>str</code> (text), and <code>bool</code> (<code>True</code>/<code>False</code>). Containers include the <code>list</code>, an ordered mutable sequence written <code>[1, 2, 3]</code>, and the <code>dict</code> (dictionary), a set of key-value pairs written <code>{'host': 'web1', 'port': 80}</code>. Lists and dicts are the workhorses of admin scripting.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Example</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>int</code></td><td><code>80</code></td><td>Whole number</td></tr><tr><td><code>float</code></td><td><code>3.14</code></td><td>Decimal</td></tr><tr><td><code>str</code></td><td><code>'web1'</code></td><td>Text</td></tr><tr><td><code>bool</code></td><td><code>True</code></td><td>True / False</td></tr><tr><td><code>list</code></td><td><code>[1, 2, 3]</code></td><td>Ordered, mutable</td></tr><tr><td><code>dict</code></td><td><code>{'k': 'v'}</code></td><td>Key-value pairs</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Built-in Modules and a Sample Script</h3><p>The standard library covers most admin needs without external packages. <code>os</code> and <code>sys</code> interact with the operating system and arguments; <code>subprocess</code> runs external commands; <code>json</code> parses and emits JSON; <code>pathlib</code> handles filesystem paths; <code>re</code> provides regular expressions. You import them with <code>import os</code> and call functions like <code>os.listdir('/etc')</code>. A short script ties it together:</p><pre><code>import os\nfor entry in os.listdir('/var/log'):\n    if entry.endswith('.log'):\n        print(entry)</code></pre><p>To check disk usage you might call <code>subprocess.run(['df', '-h'])</code>. The readable syntax and rich library are why Python has become the second language of Linux administration alongside Bash.</p><h3>Control Flow and When to Choose Python</h3><p>Python's control flow mirrors Bash's intent but with cleaner syntax. An <code>if value &gt; 10:</code> followed by an indented block, a <code>for item in mylist:</code> loop, and a <code>while condition:</code> loop cover the same ground as their shell counterparts, and a <code>def name(args):</code> defines a function that returns a real value with <code>return</code> -- not just a 0-255 status as in Bash. The practical question is when to reach for Python instead of a shell script. Bash shines at gluing command-line tools together and quick file manipulation, but it grows unwieldy once you need structured data, error handling, arithmetic beyond integers, or API calls. Python excels exactly there: parsing JSON or YAML from an API, manipulating dictionaries and lists, doing floating-point math, and handling exceptions with <code>try</code>/<code>except</code>. A rule of thumb is that if a shell script sprouts more than a few functions or starts parsing structured data with <code>awk</code> and <code>sed</code> gymnastics, it is time to rewrite it in Python.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Create a venv with <code>python3 -m venv name</code> and activate with <code>source name/bin/activate</code>; <code>pip</code> installs into it. Python uses indentation for blocks. Know the data types -- <code>int</code>, <code>bool</code>, <code>str</code>, <code>list</code> (<code>[ ]</code>), and <code>dict</code> (<code>{ }</code> key-value pairs).</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A script mixes tabs and spaces and dies with <code>TabError: inconsistent use of tabs and spaces</code>. Configuring the editor to insert four spaces and re-indenting the block fixes it -- a reminder that in Python whitespace is syntax, not decoration.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Version Control with Git", body:"<p>Every script, playbook, and configuration file in an automated environment belongs in version control, and <span class='keyterm'>Git</span> is the universal standard. Git is a <em>distributed</em> version control system: each clone is a full copy of the project history, so you can commit, branch, and inspect history entirely offline.</p><h3>Creating and Cloning Repositories</h3><p>You start tracking a directory with <code>git init</code>, which creates a hidden <code>.git</code> folder holding all history. To copy an existing remote project you run <code>git clone https://server/repo.git</code>, which downloads the full history and sets up a link back to the origin. Before your first commit you set your identity with <code>git config --global user.name 'Your Name'</code> and <code>git config --global user.email 'you@example.com'</code>, recorded on every commit you make.</p><h3>The Staging Workflow</h3><p>Git has a distinctive three-stage flow: the <span class='keyterm'>working directory</span> (your files), the <span class='keyterm'>staging area</span> (the index), and the <span class='keyterm'>repository</span> (committed history). You stage changes with <code>git add file</code> (or <code>git add .</code> for everything), then record them permanently with <code>git commit -m 'message'</code>. <code>git status</code> shows what is modified, staged, or untracked, and <code>git log</code> shows the commit history. Only staged changes go into a commit, which lets you craft focused, meaningful commits.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>git init</code> / <code>git clone</code></td><td>Create / copy a repository</td></tr><tr><td><code>git add</code></td><td>Stage changes</td></tr><tr><td><code>git commit -m</code></td><td>Record staged changes</td></tr><tr><td><code>git status</code> / <code>git log</code></td><td>Show state / history</td></tr><tr><td><code>git diff</code></td><td>Show unstaged changes</td></tr><tr><td><code>git restore</code></td><td>Discard working changes</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Branching and Merging</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>branch</span> is an independent line of development. You create one with <code>git branch feature</code> and switch to it with <code>git checkout feature</code> (or the combined <code>git checkout -b feature</code>; newer Git also offers <code>git switch -c feature</code>). Work on a branch is isolated until you fold it back in. <code>git merge feature</code>, run from the target branch, integrates the changes; if the same lines changed on both branches you resolve a <span class='keyterm'>merge conflict</span> by editing the marked file (between <code>&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;</code> and <code>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> markers) and committing. Branching is what makes parallel, safe experimentation possible.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>git branch</code></td><td>List / create branches</td></tr><tr><td><code>git checkout -b name</code></td><td>Create and switch</td></tr><tr><td><code>git merge name</code></td><td>Integrate a branch</td></tr><tr><td><code>git tag v1.0</code></td><td>Mark a commit (release)</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Local and Remote Workflow</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>remote</span> is a shared copy of the repository, conventionally named <code>origin</code>. Three commands move history between local and remote. <code>git fetch</code> downloads new commits from the remote without changing your working files. <code>git pull</code> fetches <em>and</em> merges them into your current branch in one step. <code>git push</code> uploads your local commits to the remote so teammates see them. The typical loop is: pull the latest, make and commit changes locally, then push.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Command</th><th>Direction</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>git fetch</code></td><td>Remote to local (no merge)</td></tr><tr><td><code>git pull</code></td><td>Remote to local (fetch + merge)</td></tr><tr><td><code>git push</code></td><td>Local to remote</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Tags and .gitignore</h3><p>A <span class='keyterm'>tag</span> marks a specific commit, typically a release: <code>git tag v1.0</code> creates it and <code>git push --tags</code> shares it. The <span class='keyterm'>.gitignore</span> file lists patterns Git should never track -- build artifacts, logs, secrets, and local environment files like <code>*.log</code>, <code>venv/</code>, or <code>.env</code>. Keeping generated files and credentials out of the repository is both a hygiene and a security practice; a leaked <code>.env</code> with API keys in Git history is hard to fully purge.</p><h3>Undoing Changes</h3><p>A large part of Git's value is the safety net it provides, and the exam expects familiarity with the common ways to undo work. <code>git restore file</code> (or the older <code>git checkout -- file</code>) discards uncommitted changes in the working directory, reverting a file to its last committed state. <code>git restore --staged file</code> unstages a file without losing the edits. To rewind history, <code>git reset</code> moves the branch pointer -- a soft reset keeps your changes staged while a hard reset (<code>git reset --hard</code>) discards them entirely, so the hard form is destructive and used with care. The safest way to undo a commit that has already been pushed is <code>git revert</code>, which records a new commit that reverses the earlier one, leaving history intact and shareable rather than rewritten. Choosing revert over reset on shared branches avoids forcing teammates to untangle a rewritten history.</p><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>Memorize the flow: <code>git add</code> stages, <code>git commit</code> records, <code>git push</code> uploads to the remote, <code>git pull</code> downloads and merges, <code>git fetch</code> downloads only. <code>git clone</code> copies a remote repo; <code>.gitignore</code> excludes files from tracking.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>A developer commits a <code>.env</code> file full of API keys and pushes it. Because Git history is permanent, simply deleting the file is not enough -- the keys must be rotated and the history rewritten. Adding <code>.env</code> to <code>.gitignore</code> from the start would have prevented the leak.</div>"}
);
LINUXPLUS.reading[4].push(
  {heading:"Responsible Use of AI in Linux Administration", body:"<p>Generative AI has entered the administrator's toolkit, and Linux+ XK0-006 now expects you to use it responsibly. AI assistants can accelerate work, but they introduce risks around correctness, security, and data governance that a professional must manage deliberately.</p><h3>AI Use Cases</h3><p>The most common administrative use is <span class='keyterm'>code generation</span>: drafting a Bash or Python script, an Ansible playbook, a regular expression, or a systemd unit from a plain-language description. AI also excels at explaining unfamiliar commands and error messages, summarizing log excerpts, suggesting troubleshooting steps, generating documentation, and translating a configuration from one tool's syntax to another. Used well, it turns a blank page into a reviewable first draft and shortens the loop from problem to working solution.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Use case</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Code generation</td><td>Draft a backup script or playbook</td></tr><tr><td>Explanation</td><td>Interpret a command or error message</td></tr><tr><td>Troubleshooting</td><td>Suggest causes for a symptom</td></tr><tr><td>Documentation</td><td>Generate or summarize runbooks</td></tr><tr><td>Translation</td><td>Convert config between tools</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Always Verify the Output</h3><p>The cardinal rule is that <span class='keyterm'>AI output is a draft, never an authority</span>. Large language models can <em>hallucinate</em> -- inventing command flags that do not exist, misremembering syntax, or producing code that looks plausible but is subtly wrong or destructive. You must read and understand every line before running it, confirm flags against the actual <code>man</code> pages, and never paste a generated command into a production shell unread. A suggested <code>rm -rf</code> path or an overly broad <code>chmod 777</code> can do real damage. Treat the AI as a knowledgeable but fallible junior colleague whose work you always review.</p><h3>Test in a Sandbox</h3><p>Before running AI-generated automation anywhere it matters, <span class='keyterm'>test it in a sandbox</span> -- a disposable VM, a container, or a non-production environment that mirrors production closely enough to surface problems. This contains the blast radius of any mistake and lets you observe actual behavior rather than trusting the model's description of it. Pair sandbox testing with version control so changes are reviewable and reversible, and with a <code>--check</code>-style dry run where the tool supports one.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Practice</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Verify every line</td><td>Models hallucinate flags and syntax</td></tr><tr><td>Test in a sandbox</td><td>Contains the blast radius</td></tr><tr><td>Use version control</td><td>Changes are reviewable, reversible</td></tr><tr><td>Sanitize prompts</td><td>Keeps secrets out of third parties</td></tr></tbody></table><h3>Data Governance and Secrets</h3><p>What you send to an AI service matters as much as what you get back. <span class='keyterm'>Never paste secrets</span> -- passwords, API keys, private keys, tokens, or customer data -- into a public AI tool. That data may be logged, retained, or used for training, and it leaves your control the moment you submit it. Beyond secrets, sharing internal configuration, source code, or proprietary information may violate your organization's <span class='keyterm'>data governance</span> policies and compliance obligations. Sanitize prompts by replacing real hostnames, IPs, and credentials with placeholders before asking for help.</p><h3>Local versus Public Models</h3><p>The privacy calculus changes with where the model runs. A <span class='keyterm'>public (cloud) model</span> sends your prompt to a third party; convenient and powerful, but your data leaves the premises. A <span class='keyterm'>local or private model</span> runs on your own hardware or within your organization's controlled environment, so sensitive prompts never traverse the internet. Regulated industries and security-conscious teams often mandate local or self-hosted models precisely so that proprietary code and infrastructure details stay in-house. Choosing the right deployment is itself a governance decision. Beyond where the model runs, organizations increasingly publish an <span class='keyterm'>acceptable use policy</span> for AI tools that spells out which tools are approved, what categories of data may and may not be submitted, and who is accountable for reviewing AI-generated changes before they reach production. A professional reads and follows that policy the same way they follow any other security control.</p><table><thead><tr><th>Model type</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Public / cloud</td><td>Powerful, convenient; data leaves the org</td></tr><tr><td>Local / private</td><td>Data stays in-house; you run the infrastructure</td></tr></tbody></table><div class='callout exam'><div class='lbl'>Exam tip</div>The responsible-AI essentials: always verify and understand generated output, test it in a sandbox before production, never paste secrets or sensitive data into public tools, and prefer local/private models when data governance demands it. AI assists; the administrator remains accountable.</div><div class='callout scenario'><div class='lbl'>Scenario</div>An admin pastes a full production <code>nginx.conf</code> -- including an upstream password -- into a public chatbot to debug it. The credential is now outside the organization's control and must be rotated. Sanitizing the config or using an approved local model would have avoided a reportable data-governance incident.</div>"}
);
